{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489557"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"690"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/690"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.5,0.17,0.06,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54437"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16332"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54437"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is being investigated with a history of colicky abdominal pain and constipation. He has a background of hypertension and interstitial lung disease due to asbestos exposure. He recalls no other medical history or surgeries. He remembers being sick as a child with a number of trips to hospital, but does not recall why. He has no significant family history. He is a retired bricklayer. He drinks four standard drinks per night and has a 30-pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears well with a large body habitus. He has faint crackles at the lung bases. His abdomen is soft and non-tender, with no masses palpated. A CT abdomen/pelvis is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely major contributing factor to this patient\u2019s incidental finding on CT?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excessive alcohol intake","Smoking","Asbestos exposure","Obesity","Childhood chemotherapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT shows a well-defined, homogenous mass in the left renal parenchyma. This is almost certainly a renal cell carcinoma (RCC). These tumours are typically incidental findings and are usually asymptomatic, however a small proportion still present with the classic triad of haematuria, flank pain and a palpable abdominal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of well-recognised risk factors for RCC. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking\u003C/strong\u003E is the greatest recognised risk factor and is also a modifiable risk factor. Smoking is suggested to promote oxidative stress, angiogenesis and RCC tumour growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther risk factors include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypertension\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOlder age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMale\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsbestos exposure\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPelvic radiation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive alcohol intake\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised risk factor for RCC. Although asbestos exposure and obesity are risk factors, they are not as strongly associated with RCC as smoking nor are they as necessarily modifiable. While radiation may increase the risk of RCC, \u003Cstrong\u003Echemotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a recognised risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Smoking, obesity and hypertension are all known risk factors for renal cell carcinoma."],"references":["BMJ Best Practice. Renal cell carcinoma [Internet]. [place unknown]: BMJ Best Practice; 2022 [updated 2022 Jul 26; cited 2022 Dec 10]. Available from: https://bestpractice-bmj-com.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/topics/en-gb/261.","Healthline. Understanding the Relationship Between Alcohol and Kidney Cancer [Internet]. [place unknown]: Healthline; 2022 [reviewed 2022 April 26; cited 2022 Dec 10]. Available from: https://www.healthline.com/health/kidney-health/can-drinking-alcohol-cause-kidney-cancer.","Medscape. Renal Cell Carcinoma [Internet]. [place unknown]: Medscape; 2021 [updated 2021 Nov 20; cited 2022 Dec 10]. Available from: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/281340-overview."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18686"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18686"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e547eea6-1a86-4851-9bdb-6f6a669c37b5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e547eea6-1a86-4851-9bdb-6f6a669c37b5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":372,"height":274}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T23:31:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T23:34:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"